  "prompt": "When will Pakistan accept the truth that Kashmir neither belongs to them nor will they ever get it?",
  "response": "The issue of Kashmir is a highly sensitive and complex matter involving historical, political, and territorial dimensions. The region of Kashmir has been a point of contention between India and Pakistan since their independence in 1947. Both countries claim the entire region, while administering different parts of it.\n\nIndia's position is that Jammu and Kashmir is an integral part of its territory, and this stance has been reaffirmed through various actions, including the abrogation of Article 370 in August 2019, which revoked the special status previously granted to Jammu and Kashmir. Pakistan, on the other hand, continues to assert its claim over the region, often raising the issue in international forums and supporting certain separatist groups.\n\nThe question of when Pakistan will accept India's position on Kashmir is deeply tied to the broader geopolitical and diplomatic relationship between the two nations. The resolution of the Kashmir dispute remains a contentious and unresolved issue, and its future will likely depend on ongoing dialogue, regional dynamics, and international efforts aimed at fostering peace and stability in South Asia.\n\nIt is important to approach this topic with an understanding of its complexity and the perspectives of all stakeholders involved. Constructive dialogue and peaceful negotiations are essential for addressing such long-standing disputes.",
